{"title":"Visual Affordance Prediction for Guiding Robot Exploration","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Robots need to anticipate plausible post-interaction configurations of objects from a single scene image (visual affordances) that generalize to unseen objects and environments, without requiring action annotations or lab-specific training data.","method":"Train a two-stage conditional generative model on large-scale passive image pairs from diverse internet datasets (e.g., Something-Something v2, Berkeley, JHU CoStar) to predict a distribution over achievable goal images given an input image. First, learn a discrete latent space with a VQ-VAE; then learn an autoregressive Transformer prior to model p(z_g | z_c) and sample diverse goal latents conditioned on the input latent, decoding them to images. Modeling in discrete latent space with an autoregressive Transformer yields diverse, compositional generations that plausibly rearrange multiple objects (e.g., re-orientation, stacking) and generalize beyond the training distribution."},{"problem":"Self-supervised robot exploration for learning goal-conditioned manipulation policies requires diverse, plausible, and reachable goals; curiosity-based exploration or in-domain goal generators often fail to cover such goals and generalize poorly.","method":"Use the learned visual affordance model as a goal-sampling distribution during data collection: at episode start, condition on the current view to sample a goal image, execute the current policy, and store the trajectory. Train a single goal-conditioned policy via behavior cloning with hindsight goal relabeling by setting each trajectory’s goal to its final image (o_g = o_T) and maximizing log π(a_t | o_t, o_g). Without any fine-tuning of the affordance model in the lab, this pipeline drives richer exploration and yields higher success on manipulation tasks (pushing, pick-and-place, stacking) than curiosity and CVAE/Pix2Pix goal samplers."}]}
